diagnoses.name: Acute Pharyngitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the pharynx causing sore throat, redness, and possible fever. It can be viral or bacterial in origin.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it leads to fever, sore throat, swollen lymph nodes, and fatigue. It can cause elevated white blood cell count and atypical lymphocytes.

diagnoses.name: Bacterial Tonsillitis
diagnoses.description: Infection of the tonsils causing sore throat, difficulty swallowing, and fever. Commonly caused by Streptococcus pyogenes. Leukocytosis is a common finding.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow, leading to high counts of abnormal white blood cells. Symptoms might include fatigue, fever, frequent infections, and it can cause thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial illness that develops in some people who have strep throat. It features a bright red rash that covers most of the body, sore throat, and high fever.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of inadequately treated strep throat or scarlet fever. Symptoms include fever, joint pain, and heart problems.

diagnoses.name: Aplastic Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when your body stops producing enough new blood cells, leading to fatigue and higher risk of infections. It's rare but can be associated with increases in platelet counts initially.

diagnoses.name: Myeloproliferative Disorders
diagnoses.description: Diseases of the bone marrow and blood that cause an overproduction of blood cells. Includes conditions like polycythemia vera, essential thrombocythemia, and myelofibrosis. Symptoms can include fatigue, fullness after eating, and increased risk of bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's a rare syndrome that mainly affects children. Symptoms can include fever, red eyes, erythema of the mouth or throat, and swollen, red skin.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Thrombocytosis
diagnoses.description: An elevated platelet count that occurs as a reaction to another disease or condition, such as infection, inflammation, or cancer. It's a response rather than a primary disease.

diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing malabsorption, and can lead to neurological symptoms.
A type of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that may affect any segment of the gastrointestinal tract, causing a wide range of symptoms including malabsorption and systemic manifestations.

An inflammatory disease that can affect multiple organs, but primarily affects the lungs and lymph glands. Associated with fibrosis, it can lead to neurological manifestations including headache and cognitive difficulties.
A rare bacterial infection that primarily affects the small intestine but can also affect the brain, causing symptoms such as malabsorption and neurological manifestations.

A genetic disorder that affects mostly the lungs, but also the pancreas, liver, kidneys, and intestine. It can lead to malabsorption and is characterized by fibrosis and damage to the respiratory system.
Human Immunodeficiency Virus/Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome can cause a wide range of symptoms including malabsorption. Neurological complications can manifest as cognitive difficulties.
A chronic autoimmune disease of the central nervous system that can cause cognitive difficulties, including word-finding problems, as well as other neurological symptoms.
A tick-borne illness that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including neurological manifestations such as headaches and cognitive issues if left untreated.
A systemic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, including the nervous system, leading to headaches and cognitive difficulties.

An infectious disease caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. When it spreads beyond the lungs, it can cause systemic symptoms, including monocytosis, and has been associated with malabsorption in disseminated cases.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. It's characterized by flares and remissions and can affect the joints, skin, brain, lungs, kidneys, and blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that often accompanies other immune system disorders, such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus. The two main symptoms are dry eyes and a dry mouth, but it can also cause lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Infection
diagnoses.description: A virus that attacks the body's immune system. If untreated, it can lead to the disease AIDS (acquired immunodeficiency syndrome). Symptoms can include swollen lymph nodes, oral pain due to ulcers, and general fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that originates in the lymphatic system. It can cause lymphadenopathy, which is swelling of the lymph nodes, and can also affect other parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A reaction similar to hives that affects deeper layers of the skin. It can be triggered by allergies, medications, and other factors. Angioedema often causes severe swelling around the eyes and lips, and it can also affect the genitalia, hence relating to vulvodynia.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing inflammation in blood vessels throughout your body. The signs and symptoms can vary widely but may include mouth sores, genital sores, eye inflammation, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. It can cause painful rashes that spread and blister, leading to the top layer of skin to die and shed.

diagnoses.name: Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic or irritant reaction that causes a painful or itchy skin rash. It can be triggered by various substances, including those encountered in sexual activity, which might relate to the symptoms of vulvodynia.

diagnoses.name: Hidradenitis Suppurativa
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition featuring lumps in places such as the armpits or groin. It's thought to occur when hair follicles become obstructed. Complications include infection or scarring.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory bowel disease that affects the lining of the digestive tract. It can cause abdominal pain, severe diarrhea, fatigue, weight loss, and malnutrition. Inflammation caused by Crohn's disease can involve different areas of the digestive tract in different people.

diagnoses.name: Constitutional delay of growth and puberty
diagnoses.description: A common cause for delayed puberty not associated with a pathological condition. Individuals eventually develop normally without treatment.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the sinuses that lasts more than 12 weeks. Symptoms include coryza (nasal congestion), facial pain, and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by unreasonable thoughts and fears (obsessions) that lead to compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic response causing itchy, watery eyes, sneezing, and other similar symptoms. It can contribute to symptoms like coryza.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Can lead to delayed puberty and may contribute to neurocognitive issues like obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.name: Kallmann Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by delayed or absent puberty and an impaired sense of smell. It's a form of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism.

diagnoses.name: Turner Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A chromosomal disorder in females lacking part or all of an X chromosome, leading to delayed puberty among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: Mental health disorders characterized by significant worry or fear that is difficult to control, contributing to obsessive-compulsive behaviors and sometimes physical symptoms like headache.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition causing multiple symptoms, most notably a painful headache. Can be associated with hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Stress
diagnoses.description: Physical and psychological response to intense, prolonged pressures. It can exacerbate or initiate the development of symptoms like headaches, obsessive-compulsive behaviors, and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of moderate to severe throbbing and pulsating pain on one side of the head. The aura includes visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear before the headache and last for about 20 to 60 minutes.

diagnoses.name: Transient ischemic attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. It doesn't cause permanent damage. Symptoms such as aphasia, weakness, and vision disturbances can occur.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, causing brain tissue to be deprived of oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, aphasia, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It's an autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including difficulties with vision (scintillation), muscle weakness, and difficulty with coordination and speech.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, loss of consciousness, or convulsions, associated with abnormal electrical activity in the brain. It can present with headache, temporary paralysis or weakness, and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain that can be cancerous or noncancerous. Depending on its location, it can cause headaches, weakness, visual disturbances, and speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.description: Low blood sugar, a condition that can lead to symptoms such as headache, weakness, visual disturbances, and in severe cases, neurological problems or unconsciousness.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition where you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, causing fatigue, weakness, and headache among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs, potentially causing a wide range of symptoms, including headache, weakness, and neurological symptoms like visual disturbances and cognitive difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Intracranial hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Bleeding within the skull that can result from a variety of injuries or disorders. Symptoms can include severe headache, weakness, vomiting, seizures, visual disturbances, confusion, and in severe cases, aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is accompanied by visual disturbances (scintillation), and may also include aphasia, along with nausea, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include aphasia, vertigo, and possibly nausea or vomiting depending on the area of the brain affected.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inner ear disorder that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. It often includes nausea and vomiting as well.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal cell growth in the brain that can cause neurological symptoms including aphasia, seizures (which could manifest as scintillation), vomiting, and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it’s a brief interruption of blood flow to a part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, which may cause symptoms similar to a stroke, such as aphasia and vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Visual disturbances like scintillation could occur during a seizure.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from a restricted blood supply to the back of the brain, causing dizziness, vertigo, double vision, nausea, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can cause symptoms such as visual disturbances (scintillation), dizziness (vertigo), and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the main nerve leading from the inner ear to the brain. Pressure from the tumor can cause vertigo, nausea, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A type of stroke caused by bleeding within the brain tissue itself, which can lead to symptoms like nausea, vomiting, aphasia, and altered consciousness.
